PK, is topic ko bhi Evolution of Pain + Feynman method se samjhte hain. API Gateway tabhi properly samajh aata hai jab monolith → microservices transition ka pain samjhte hain.

API Gateway
1️⃣ Evolution of Pain (Problem Without API Gateway)

Imagine ek microservices architecture:

Client
   │
   ├── Product Service
   ├── Order Service
   ├── Payment Service
   ├── Review Service
   └── Recommendation Service

Client ko agar “My Orders” page load karna hai to:

Mobile App ko directly call karna padega:

GET /products
GET /invoice
GET /reviews
GET /recommendations
Problems
1️⃣ Too many API calls

Mobile client ko multiple APIs call karne padte hain.

1 screen = 5 API calls

Latency increase.

2️⃣ Client complexity

Client ko pata hona chahiye:

product service location
invoice service location
review service location

Agar service change ho jaye:

Client update karna padega
3️⃣ Security duplication

Har microservice me:

Authentication
Rate limiting
Logging

Repeat karna padta hai.

4️⃣ No centralized control

Example:

Rate limit
Authentication
Caching
Monitoring

Sab jagah implement karna padta hai.

2️⃣ The Cure (API Gateway)

API Gateway acts like:

Single entry point for all clients

Architecture becomes:

Client
   │
   ▼
API Gateway
   │
   ├── Product Service
   ├── Order Service
   ├── Invoice Service
   └── Review Service

Client sirf API Gateway ko call karega.

Gateway decide karega:

Which microservice to call
3️⃣ Core Idea (Difference from Load Balancer)

This is the most common interview confusion.

Load Balancer

Distributes traffic between same service instances.

Example:

Request → Load Balancer
           │
           ├── Order Service Instance 1
           ├── Order Service Instance 2
           └── Order Service Instance 3

Load balancer API endpoint nahi samajhta.

API Gateway

Routes requests to different services.

Example:

/orders  → Order Service
/invoice → Invoice Service
/review  → Review Service

So:

API Gateway = intelligent router
Load Balancer = traffic distributor
4️⃣ Where Both Fit in Architecture

Typical architecture:

Client
   │
   ▼
API Gateway
   │
   ▼
Load Balancer
   │
   ▼
Service Instances

Example:

Client
  │
  ▼
API Gateway
  │
  ├── Order LB → Order Instances
  └── Invoice LB → Invoice Instances
5️⃣ Major Features of API Gateway
1️⃣ API Composition

Very important.

Example:

User opens:

My Orders page

Required data:

Product details
Invoice details
Reviews
Recommendations

Without gateway:

Client → 4 API calls

With gateway:

Client → 1 API

Gateway internally calls:

Product Service
Invoice Service
Review Service
Recommendation Service

Then merges response.

2️⃣ Authentication

Instead of verifying token everywhere:

Order Service
Payment Service
Review Service

We do it once at gateway.

Flow:

Client
   │
   ▼
API Gateway
   │
Validate JWT
   │
   ▼
Microservices
3️⃣ Rate Limiting

Gateway can control traffic.

Example rules:

10 requests per minute per user

If exceeded:

HTTP 429 Too Many Requests

Helps prevent:

DDoS attacks
API abuse
4️⃣ API Throttling

More granular control.

Example:

/invoice API → max 10 req/min per user

If user sends:

11th request → blocked
5️⃣ Burst Control

Handles traffic spikes.

Example:

Burst limit = 500 requests

If 1000 requests come instantly:

500 processed
500 queued/rejected
6️⃣ Service Discovery

Microservices scale dynamically.

Instances:

Order Service
 ├── instance1
 ├── instance2
 └── instance3

But instances keep changing.

Service discovery tools track them.

Examples:

Eureka
Consul
Zookeeper

Gateway asks:

Where is Order Service?

Service discovery returns:

instance2:8080
6️⃣ Other Capabilities

API Gateway can also do:

Request Transformation

Example:

Client request:

GET /orders

Gateway converts:

GET /orders?userId=123
Response Transformation

Backend response:

{
  "name":"phone",
  "price":500
}

Gateway converts to mobile friendly format.

Caching

Gateway caches responses.

Example:

Product catalog

Next request served from cache.

Logging & Monitoring

Gateway logs:

request
response
latency
errors

Useful for observability.

7️⃣ How Gateway Handles Millions of Requests

Important interview question.

Answer:

API Gateway is not a single instance

Architecture:

Client
  │
  ▼
DNS Load Balancer
  │
  ▼
API Gateway Cluster
  │
  ▼
Load Balancers
  │
  ▼
Microservices
8️⃣ Multi-Region Architecture

Large systems deploy gateways in regions.

Example:

Region 1 → Mumbai
Region 2 → Chennai
Region 3 → Singapore

Each region has:

API Gateway
Load Balancers
Microservices

DNS routes traffic to nearest region.

Example:

User in India → Mumbai region
User in Singapore → Singapore region

Tools:

AWS Route53
Azure Traffic Manager
Cloudflare
9️⃣ Availability Zones

Each region has multiple data centers.

Example:

Mumbai Region
   │
   ├── AZ1 (Data center)
   └── AZ2 (Data center)

If one AZ fails:

Traffic → other AZ

High availability maintained.

🔟 Real World API Gateway Tools

Examples used in industry:

Kong
AWS API Gateway
Netflix Zuul
NGINX
Apigee
Traefik
11️⃣ Mental Model

Remember this simple chain:

DNS → API Gateway → Load Balancer → Microservices

Where:

API Gateway → routing + security
Load Balancer → distribute traffic

